# 🏗️ XYZ Education: Infrastructure Model & TCO Calculator Guide

## Business Profile (Assumptions)

| Parameter | Value | Rationale |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Platform Type | K-12 Online Education (Live + VOD) | Comparable to VIPKid/Zuoyebang/Byju's |
| Registered Students | 5.2 Million | Top-tier APAC EdTech scale |
| Peak Concurrent Users | 420,000 | ~8% concurrency ratio (industry: 3-10%) |
| Large Class (大班课) | 70% of traffic, 200+ students/class | 1 teacher → many. Low interactivity, high transcoding |
| Small Group (小班课) | 30% of traffic, 10-25 students/class | Multi-way video. SFU architecture |
| Peak Hours | 16:00 - 21:00 (5hrs daily) + weekends | After-school tutoring pattern |
| Markets | Mainland China, Singapore, Hong Kong | PIPL/PDPA/PDPO jurisdictions |

---

## Workload Decomposition (Bottom-Up)

### Tier 1: Video Transcoding Engine (The Cost Monster)

This is **70-75% of total compute**. Live video must be transcoded in real-time from a teacher's camera feed into 4 adaptive bitrate outputs (1080p/720p/480p/360p, H.264).

| Metric | Calculation | Result |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Concurrent large classes | 420k × 70% ÷ 200 students/class | **1,470 classes** |
| vCPUs per large class | 4 output resolutions × 2 vCPUs/stream | **8 vCPUs** |
| Large class total | 1,470 × 8 | **11,760 vCPUs** |
| Concurrent small groups | 420k × 30% ÷ 20 students/group | **6,300 groups** |
| vCPUs per small group | SFU relay + 2 composite feeds × 2 vCPUs | **4 vCPUs** |
| Small group total | 6,300 × 4 | **25,200 vCPUs** |
| **Transcoding subtotal** | | **36,960 vCPUs** |
| + 10% headroom | Safety margin for encoding spikes | **~40,650 vCPUs** |

> [!NOTE]
> Small groups are surprisingly more expensive than large classes because EVERY student's video feed needs processing (even if just relayed via SFU), whereas large classes only process the teacher's single feed.

### Tier 2: Media Servers (WebRTC/RTMP Signaling & Relay)

| Metric | Value |
|:---|:---|
| Purpose | WebRTC signaling, STUN/TURN relay, RTMP ingest |
| vCPU estimate | ~6,400 vCPUs |
| Rationale | ~1 vCPU per 80 concurrent WebRTC connections. 420k ÷ 80 ≈ 5,250 + overhead |

### Tier 3: Application / API Layer

| Metric | Value |
|:---|:---|
| Purpose | User auth, class scheduling, payment, homework submission, admin dashboard |
| vCPU estimate | ~3,200 vCPUs |
| Rationale | Standard web app tier. ~1 vCPU per 150 concurrent API users |

### Tier 4: Database Tier

| Metric | Value |
|:---|:---|
| Purpose | PostgreSQL/MySQL clusters, Redis cache, ElasticSearch |
| vCPU estimate | ~2,400 vCPUs |
| RAM requirement | **High memory**: 128-256GB per DB node |
| Rationale | User profiles, class records, billing, real-time analytics |

### Tier 5: AI / ML Inference

| Metric | Value |
|:---|:---|
| Purpose | Speech recognition, auto-grading, content recommendation |
| vCPU estimate | ~2,000 vCPUs (CPU inference) |
| Note | Could also use GPU instances — but CPU inference is more common for cost-sensitive EdTech |

---

## Total Infrastructure Summary

| Tier | vCPUs | % of Total |
|:---|---:|---:|
| Video Transcoding | 40,650 | 74% |
| Media/WebRTC | 6,400 | 12% |
| Application/API | 3,200 | 6% |
| Database | 2,400 | 4% |
| AI Inference | 2,000 | 4% |
| **TOTAL** | **54,650** | **100%** |

### Storage

| Type | Amount | Purpose |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Block (SSD/NVMe) | 500 TB | Hot database storage, transcoding cache |
| Object (HDD/Ceph) | 5 PB | Recorded class archival, compliance logs |

### Network

| Metric | Value | Notes |
|:---|:---|:---|
| Monthly Egress | 1.5 PB/month | Video streaming to students |
| Annual Egress | 18 PB/year | This is the #1 AWS cost driver after compute |

