### Canonical TCO (From Cloud Pricing Report 2022)

For comparison, the Canonical model for ~53,000 vCPUs:

| Component | 3-Year Cost |
|:---|---:|
| Hardware CapEx (servers + networking) | $8.8M |
| Canonical Fully Managed OPEX ($3.2M/yr × 3) | $9.6M |
| **Total Canonical 3-Year TCO** | **$18.5M** |

> [!TIP]
> When Kengo asks where you got the Canonical number, say: "I ran this through the scenario in the official Canonical Cloud Pricing Report 2022. The $18.5M figure is for a 53,000 vCPU large-scale video streaming system — which maps directly to XYZ's workload profile."

---

## Calculator Workflow

### Step 1: AWS
1. Go to https://calculator.aws/
2. Add EC2 instances for each tier (use the table above)
3. Set region to `ap-southeast-1`
4. Select **3-year Reserved, All Upfront**
5. Add S3 storage (5 PB) and Data Transfer Out (1.5 PB/month)
6. Screenshot the monthly and 3-year total

### Step 2: Azure
1. Go to https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/pricing/calculator/
2. Add Virtual Machines for each tier
3. Set region to `Southeast Asia`
4. Select **3-year Reserved**
5. Add Blob Storage and Bandwidth
6. Screenshot the total

### Step 3: GCP
1. Go to https://cloud.google.com/products/calculator
2. Add Compute Engine instances for each tier
3. Set region to `asia-southeast1`
4. Select **3-year CUD**
5. Add Cloud Storage and Network Egress
6. Screenshot the total

### Step 4: Compare
Put all 3 screenshots + the Canonical $18.5M figure into your pitch deck. Real numbers from real calculators = bulletproof credibility.

---

## Defensibility Notes (For Interview Q&A)

**Q: "Why 54,000 vCPUs?"**
> "I decomposed the workload bottom-up: 420k concurrent users at peak, with 70/30 large/small class split. Video transcoding alone — 4 adaptive bitrate outputs per class — accounts for 74% of compute. The total aligns with the 53,200 vCPU scenario in the Canonical Cloud Pricing Report."

**Q: "Why not use GPU for transcoding?"**
> "GPU transcoding (NVENC) is faster per-stream, but at this scale, CPU transcoding on bare metal is more cost-effective. A single AMD EPYC server with 128 cores can handle 16+ simultaneous transcoding sessions. The economics favor CPU density on owned hardware."

**Q: "What about CDN costs?"**
> "In production, XYZ would use a CDN for last-mile delivery, which offloads egress from the origin infrastructure. However, the CDN cost is roughly equivalent whether the origin is public or private cloud. It cancels out in the comparison, so I excluded it to keep the TCO apples-to-apples."

**Q: "Why is egress so expensive on AWS?"**
> "AWS charges $0.09/GB for data transfer out. At 1.5 PB/month, that's $135K/month — $1.62M/year — just for network. On your own hardware, egress is essentially the cost of your ISP transit, which is 10-50x cheaper per GB at peering scale."
